text: Some Pig
label: HH3

text: All kids seem to love Charlotte’s
label: BODY

text: Web, the classic children’s story by E. B.
label: BODY

text: White, of Wilbur the pig and his faithful
label: BODY

text: friend Charlotte the spider. Even kids who
label: BODY

text: haven’t read the book have seen the movie
label: BODY

text: and know that Charlotte is loving, wise and
label: BODY

text: resourceful. To save Wilbur from his fate as
label: BODY

text: bacon, she spins the immortal words “Some
label: BODY

text: Pig” with webbing over his sty, and
label: BODY

text: eventually makes him the world’s most
label: BODY

text: famous farm animal.
label: BODY

text: Spiders don’t really do that, needless
label: BODY

text: to say. And everyone seems to hate spiders.
label: BODY

text: Most people reach for a can of bug spray at
label: BODY

text: the sight of a spider, or like Garfield, flatten
label: BODY

text: the spider with one stamp. But spiders are
label: BODY

text: common enough in agricultural fields that
label: BODY

text: they seriously reduce the numbers of insect
label: BODY

text: pests. The financial benefit of spiders to pest
label: BODY

text: control is estimated at over one million
label: BODY

text: dollars per year in New York State alone.
label: BODY

text: Spiders eat insects–they’re not looking for
label: BODY

text: humans to bite. Dangerously venomous
label: BODY

text: spiders are rare in New York State; few of
label: BODY

text: us will ever even see one.
label: BODY

text: August is the month of orb weavers,
label: BODY

text: the big, beautiful gold-and-black spiders that
label: BODY

text: 5rivers@dec.state.ny.us
label: BODY

text: spin round webs in the fields and gardens.
label: BODY

text: There’s no need to fear them, they’re
label: BODY

text: harmless to people and will help control
label: BODY

text: pests in the garden. To find out more about
label: BODY

text: spiders, join us on a Spider Search on
label: BODY

text: August 22 at 7:00 PM. You might not love
label: BODY

text: every creepy-crawly spider you see out in
label: BODY

text: the meadow--but try to see a little Charlotte
label: BODY

text: in her.
label: BODY

text: –Anita Sanchez
label: BODY

text: (Thanks to former Naturalist Intern Andy
label: BODY

text: Fyfe for spider research.)

text: Five Rivers Environmental Education Center

text: Summer Program Schedule 2006
label: HH1

text: Programs are free of charge unless otherwise noted. Dress for the weather!  We regret that
label: BODY

text: we cannot accommodate organized youth groups at these programs. Call to make special
label: BODY

text: arrangements.
label: BODY

text: We welcome those who have any type of physical challenge to all of our programs. If
label: BODY

text: you call ahead to let us know your needs, we will be happy to learn how we can best serve you.
label: BODY

text: For further information or for pre-registration, call Five Rivers at 518-475-0291. In the event
label: BODY

text: of severe weather, programs may be canceled. Please call the Center to confirm.
label: BODY

text: Saturday, July 1
label: BODY

text: Family Fun: 10th ANNUAL BUTTERFLY COUNT
label: BODY

text: Join us for a close-up look at common butterflies of the Capital District as we continue our
label: BODY

text: annual catch-and-release census. Nets or binoculars are welcome. Call to pre-register by June 28.
label: BODY

text: Thursday, July 6
label: BODY

text: Family Program: STREAM WALK
label: BODY

text: Parents and children are invited to wade our streams and examine their animal life. Call to
label: BODY

text: pre-register by July 3. Materials fee: FOFR members $3.00/family. Non-members $5.00/family.
label: BODY

text: Tuesday, July 11
label: BODY

text: SQUIRRELS IN OUR BACKYARD
label: BODY

text: Chipmunks, woodchucks, and grey, red and flying squirrels are all are members of the
label: BODY

text: squirrel family. Join us as we explore some of the behaviors of these fascinating animals.
label: BODY

text: Thursday July 13
label: BODY

text: FERNS
label: BODY

text: A beginner-level class on the identification of some common ferns along the Vlomankill.
label: BODY

text: Saturday, July 15
label: BODY

text: GPS-TREKKING (Global Positioning System)
label: BODY

text: An introduction to GPS units for experienced users and beginners. Please call to pre-register
label: BODY

text: by July 13. Our supply of units to borrow is limited--call early to reserve one.
label: BODY

text: Saturday, July 15
label: BODY

text: DRAGONS & DAMSELS
label: BODY

text: A pond-side observation of dragonflies and damselflies. Bring binoculars or use ours.
label: BODY

text: Tuesday, July 18
label: BODY

text: BATS IN FLIGHT
label: BODY

text: Join a DEC biologist for a talk on bats, followed by a walk to watch  the bats emerge from
label: BODY

text: the “bat barn” and begin their evening mosquito hunts.
label: BODY

text: Thursday, July 20
label: BODY

text: FLOWER IDENTIFICATION
label: BODY

text: During this adult-level class we’ll learn plant family relationships as well as basic principles
label: BODY

text: of identification, and discuss traditional uses for plants, from magic to medicine to food.
label: BODY

text: Friday, July 21
label: BODY

text: FROGWATCH
label: BODY

text: We’ll listen for the deep-throated call of the bullfrog, and search for other wildlife, too.
label: BODY

text: Tuesday, July 25
label: BODY

text: VLOMANKILL TRAIL WALK
label: BODY

text: Come explore the beautiful, shady Vlomankill trail on a natural history walk that covers the
label: BODY

text: geologic past and the ecology of the present.
label: BODY

text: Saturday, July 29
label: BODY

text: Watchable Wildlife: WATERFOWL
label: BODY

text: Join us on an outdoor survey of our ponds as we take a gander at common ducks and geese.
label: BODY

text: Tuesday, August 1
label: BODY

text: FLOWERS OF LAWN AND MEADOW
label: BODY

text: Summer is the time for colorful flowers underfoot! On this walk we’ll identify some common
label: BODY

text: wildflowers and discuss their natural history, as well as their ancient myths and folklore.
label: BODY

text: Thursday, August 3
label: BODY

text: Family Program: MORNING IN THE GARDEN
label: BODY

text: Explore the wonders of the summer garden. A craft will be included. Call to pre-register by
label: BODY

text: Aug. 1. Materials fee: FOFR members $3.00/family. Non-members $5.00/family.
label: BODY

text: Friday, August 4
label: BODY

text: FROGWATCH
label: BODY

text: Come listen for the deep-throated calls of the grand-daddy of all the frogs, the bullfrog, as
label: BODY

text: well as green frogs and other wetlands wildlife, as we monitor our amphibian populations.
label: BODY

text: Saturday, August 5
label: BODY

text: Family Program: HIKE ON THE NORTH LOOP
label: BODY

text: A 2 ½  mile trek with stops along the way. Wear sturdy shoes, bring water, a snack,
label: BODY

text: sunblock, and a hat. Bring insect repellent, but don’t put it on until it’s needed. Other things to
label: BODY

text: consider: binoculars, camera, journal, magnifiers, sketch pad, pack.  Please pre-register by August 3.
label: BODY

text: FIVE RIVERS FAMILY CAMP-OUT
label: BODY

text: Friday, August 11, 5:00 PM to Saturday August 12, 11:00 AM
label: BODY

text: Picnics - tents - campfire - night walk - early morning bird walk - stream exploration!
label: BODY

text: This family-oriented overnight program will introduce your family to backyard camping at its best.
label: BODY

text: When you call to pre-register, a materials and activities list will be sent.
label: BODY

text: Fee for a family of four (or fewer): FOFR Members- $10.00, non-members $15.00.

text: Each additional person: Members $2.00, non-members $3.00.

text: Saturday, August 12
label: BODY

text: CHEROKEE LEAF PRINTING
label: BODY

text: A traditional Native American craft, using plants to print fabric. Bring a cotton t-shirt if you
label: BODY

text: like; we have some fabric, too. Call to pre-register by August 10. Materials fee $1.00 per family.

label: BODY

text: NATURE JOURNALING FOR ADULTS
label: BODY

text: Learn how to start your own nature journal and try out some of our drawing materials. If it
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Tuesday, August 22
label: BODY

text: SPIDER SEARCH
label: BODY

text: A walk to search the meadow for a wild variety of late-summer spiders.

label: BODY

text: ROGER TORY PETERSON’S BIRDS
label: BODY

text: Through his Field Guide to the Birds, Roger Tory Peterson launched our national
label: BODY

text: preoccupation with bird watching. Join us on a commemorative field study of birds, the
label: BODY

text: “environmental litmus paper,” as we celebrate the date of the late Dr. Peterson’s birth 98 years ago.
label: BODY

text: Thursday, August 29
label: BODY

text: INSECTS
label: BODY

text: By now the insects are abundant and showy--and fun to catch, observe, identify and release!
label: BODY
